statement.p:
 A tree on vertices 0,1,2,\ldots, n-1 rooted at vertex 0 is ascending when the label of each child is larger than the label of its parent. For example, there are two ascending trees on 3 vertices:



\begin{tikzpicture}

\draw[thick] (-.5, -.67) -- (0,0) -- (.5, -.67);
\draw[fill] (0,0) circle (2pt);
\draw[fill] (-.5,-.67) circle (2pt);
\draw[fill] (.5,-.67) circle (2pt);

\node[above] at (0,0) {0};
\node[right] at (.5,-.67) {1};
\node[left] at (-.5,-.67) {2};

\begin{scope}[shift={(3,0)}]

\draw[thick] (0,0) -- (1, -1.34);
\draw[fill] (0,0) circle (2pt);
\draw[fill] (1,-1.34) circle (2pt);
\draw[fill] (.5,-.67) circle (2pt);

\node[above] at (0,0) {0};
\node[right] at (.5,-.67) {1};
\node[right] at (1,-1.34) {2};

\end{scope}

\end{tikzpicture}



Use induction on n to prove that the number of ascending trees is (n-1)!.
